Ben Maurer wrote:
&gt; Hello,
&gt;
&gt; I&#39;m writing a custom JUnit test runner so that I can run tests in
&gt; different processes. THis is necessary for an online grading system in
&gt; which we want to ensure that the student has the best chance of
&gt; passing each test -- if one test times out, we don&#39;t want to abort the
&gt; whole process.
&gt;
&gt; When I use the @Test(timeout=...) attribute, it seems to take twice as
&gt; long as I specify to run the code. I suspect that the following is the
&gt; issue:
&gt;
&gt; boolean terminated= service.awaitTermination(timeout,
&gt; 					TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
&gt; 			if (!terminated)
&gt; 				service.shutdownNow();
&gt; 			result.get(timeout, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS); // throws the exception
&gt; if one occurred during the invocation
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; If shutdownNow fails to shut things down (as sometimes happens if you
&gt; are in a while (true) loop the jvm can&#39;t abort), it takes two times
&gt; the timeout to get past this code segment. Shouldn&#39;t the timeout
&gt; passed to result.get be very small?
